english:
  title: Edict Conferring the Title of Crown Prince
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    We issue this edict to the Prince Yi, whose name we revere:

    Your mind shines with clarity and wisdom, your bearing reflects grace and refinement. Having now taken your place as second to the throne, you must be properly established in the name befitting the heir. Therefore, following the rites of our ancestors, we bestow upon you this singular honor and blessing.

    We dispatch our emissaries—Vice Commander Choi Hong-jae, bearing the rank of Acting Grand Commandant and Chief Minister, and Deputy Envoy Mun Gong-in, bearing the rank of Acting Minister of the Right—both adorned with ribbons and insignia, to travel to your domain and formally invest you as Crown Prince. With this appointment, we present to you the seal and cord of office, ceremonial robes and belt, bow and arrows, vessels of gold and silver, bolts of silk, grain stores, saddles and steeds, and sundry precious things as recorded in the accompanying inventory.

    Receive these tokens with reverence.
  footnotes:
    - This is an official edict of imperial appointment, part of the formal ceremony establishing a prince as heir to the throne during the Goryeo dynasty.
    - The lengthy titles and official ranks of the emissaries reflect the elaborate bureaucratic system of medieval Korea, emphasizing the solemnity of the occasion.
